<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="mainText">
Natural history. This species occupies a relatively narrow altitudinal range (collected between 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.655" metricValueMax="1.83" metricValueMin="1.48" unit="m" value="1655.0" valueMax="1830.0" valueMin="1480.0">
<date value="1480" valueMax="1830">1480- 1830</date>
m
</quantity>
), which coincides with sandstone rock formations. Above 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000m</quantity>
sandstone is virtually absent, and granite and basalt formations dominate. The specimens from Ha Mphahama were collected on a sandstone 
<pageBreakToken pageId="22" pageNumber="23" start="start">ridge</pageBreakToken>
and constructed their webs underneath rocks lying on the soil surface. The webs followed a winding path that varied from ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" unit="cm" value="6.0">6 cm</quantity>
in early instar immatures to ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" unit="cm" value="18.0">18 cm</quantity>
in one adult female. Prey remains included 
<taxonomicName family="Formicidae" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="family">Formicidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:15379" family="Curculionidae" lsidName-HNS="Curculionidae Latreille" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="family">Curculionidae</taxonomicName>
and small 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:19938" family="Gryllidae" lsidName-HNS="Gryllidae " pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="family">Gryllidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">Distribution. Known from Eastern Cape Province, South Africa, and Lesotho (Fig. 21).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
